{
  "local_port": 50592,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "What are the best online coding schools available?",
  "response": "As of my last update in October 2023, there are several well-regarded online coding schools that cater to different needs, skill levels, and learning preferences. Here are some of the best options:\n\n1. **Codecademy**:\n   - **Overview**: Offers interactive coding lessons across various programming languages and web development technologies.\n   - **Pros**: User-friendly interface with hands-on coding exercises. Good for beginners.\n   - **Cons**: Limited depth in some subjects for advanced users.\n\n2. **freeCodeCamp**:\n   - **Overview**: A nonprofit organization that offers a comprehensive curriculum in web development, data visualization, and more entirely for free.\n   - **Pros**: Hands-on projects, a supportive community, and a well-structured learning path.\n   - **Cons**: Some learners may find the self-directed format challenging without external support.\n\n3. **Udacity**:\n   - **Overview**: Known for its \"Nanodegree\" programs in various tech fields, including AI, programming, data science, and more.\n   - **Pros**: Offers industry-relevant projects and mentorship support.\n   - **Cons**: Can be on the pricier side compared to other options.\n\n4. **Coursera**:\n   - **Overview**: Partners with universities and institutions to offer courses in programming, data science, and software engineering.\n   - **Pros**: Access to university-level education and specializations.\n   - **Cons**: Some courses may not be as interactive as those on other platforms.\n\n5. **edX**:\n   - **Overview**: Offers high-quality courses from universities and organizations on various programming languages and topics.\n   - **Pros**: Can earn verified certificates and even pursue MicroMasters programs.\n   - **Cons**: Less hands-on compared to coding bootcamps.\n\n6. **Le Wagon**:\n   - **Overview**: Focuses on intensive coding bootcamps with a strong emphasis on web development and data science.\n   - **Pros**: Strong community and supportive network for alumni.\n   - **Cons**: More expensive than many online courses.\n\n7. **General Assembly**:\n   - **Overview**: Provides immersive coding bootcamps and part-time courses focused on web development, data science, and UX/UI design.\n   - **Pros**: Strong job placement assistance and industry connections.\n   - **Cons**: Higher cost; may not be suitable for those looking for free options.\n\n8. **App Academy**:\n   - **Overview**: Offers a full-time software engineering bootcamp with a focus on getting students job-ready.\n   - **Pros**: Pay only after securing a job (Income Share Agreement) option.\n   - **Cons**: Intense curriculum that might be overwhelming.\n\n9. **Treehouse**:\n   - **Overview**: Provides a large library of video tutorials and tracks in web development, design, and business.\n   - **Pros**: Engaging videos and quizzes; great for beginners.\n   - **Cons**: Subscription-based and less interactive compared to some other platforms.\n\n10. **Skillshare**:\n    - **Overview**: Features a variety of coding courses from various instructors.\n    - **Pros**: Flexible learning and diverse topics.\n    - **Cons**: Course quality can vary widely depending on the instructor.\n\nWhen choosing a coding school, consider factors such as your learning style, budget, and career goals. Many of these platforms offer free trials or introductory courses, allowing you to explore before committing.",
